N2  - Introduction and Aims: Frailty is a common concern in chronic kidney disease (CKD) population, which is significantly related to fall, disability, hospitalization and mortality. However, there are few reports evaluating the frailty phenotype in a relatively stable, prevalent maintenance dialysis (MD) population. We studied the prevalence, correlates and clinical consequences of frailty in MD patients. Methods: This ongoing study has recruited ambulatory MD patients aged ≥20 years old on hemodialysis or peritoneal dialysis ≥6 months, without hospitalization history for the previous 3 months. Study participants completed the Korean version of Kidney Disease Quality of Life Short Form 36 (KDQOL-36) and clinical data were obtained by review of medical records. We adopted frailty phenotype composed of the following components; 1) unintentional weight loss more than 4.5 Kg or 5% of the previous body weight for the last 1 year, 2) physical inactivity, 3) RAND-36 physical function (PF) scale <75 and vitality (VT) scale <55 as surrogates for weakness/slowness and exhaustion, respectively. Low PF scale was scored as 2 points and other components as 1 point for each. Those with 3 or more points were considered as “frail”. Results: The 1,100 participants evaluated were 55.5±13.2 years of age (mean±SD) on MD for 5.2±4.6 years; 55.8% were male. The overall prevalence of frailty was 33.4%, increased with aging (P<0.001); 19.4% in less than 40 years old, 18.2% in 40s, 32.6% in 50s, 38.4% in 60s and 61.3% in 70 years or older. Frail patients were more likely to be female (39.9 vs 28.2%; P<0.001), lower education level (P<0.001) and unemployed (39.4 vs 18.1%; P<0.001) and they also had significantly lower mean value of hemoglobin (10.4 vs 10.6 g/dL; P<0.001), blood urea nitrogen (58.1 vs 61.3 mg/dL; P =0.001) and serum creatinine (9.5 vs 10.8 mg/dL; P<0.001). Interestingly, frailty was associated with higher level of inflammation markers such as high sensitive C-reactive protein (hs-CRP) (1.0 vs 0.7 mg/dL; P =0.019) and ferritin (219.3 vs 187.5 ng/mL; P =0.002). In multivariate analysis. female gender (odds ratio (OR), 2.01 [95% CI, 1.21-3.31]), older age (OR, 1.05 [95% CI, 1.03-1.07]) and higher hs-CRP (OR, 1.31 [95% CI, 1.13-1.51]) showed significant association with frailty. The presence of frailty was associated also with fall-related injury for the past 1 year (OR, 1.62 [95% CI, 1.14-2.30]) and current disability (OR, 8.27 [95% CI, 5.35-12.78]). Conclusions: Frailty is extremely common even in a relatively healthy subset of prevalent MD patients. Frailty is independently associated with female gender, older age and higher inflammation state, which appears to be related also with adverse clinical outcomes such as fall-related injury and disability. Nephrologists should be more aware of and rank the prevention, early detection and treatment of frailty into high priority in the management of MD patients.
